courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. gain basic understanding on the latest advancements in biomedical sciences that are pertinent to modern society;
2. better appreciate the social impacts of biomedical research, health monitoring and disease treatment;
3. recognize how biomedical scientists can contribute to the Hong Kong healthcare community by developing and applying innovation and technology.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. understand the organization of human body and appreciate how different organs interconnect with each other;
2. describe both the gross and histological features of important organs and understand how their structures are correlated with their functions;
3. understand the clinical significance of various human structures.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. understand the structure of proteins and appreciate the importance of enzymes in biochemical reactions;
2. describe the structural-functional relationship of biomolecules in human body;
3. describe the metabolic pathways of carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and nucleic acids and to understand their inter-relationship;
4. understand the basics of cellular biochemistry;
5. analyse and explain experimental data of biochemical experiments in laboratory reports.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
discuss the structural-functional characteristics of biomolecules, particularly the roles of enzymes
in maintaining the biochemical processes of the human body;
illustrate how genes are regulated and pass onto the offspring, process and retrieve gene and protein information
using typical bioinformatics platforms;
describe the structure, functions and properties of cellular components,
and the importance of cellular processes;
describe the principles of cell and tissue engineering, process development,
and discuss their applications in modern medicine.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. understand the basic principles of statistical inference and hypothesis testing;
2. recognize the effects of bias and confounding in epidemiological studies;
3. appreciate common epidemiological designs and their strengths and limitations;
4. understand common statistical tests and their assumptions and limitations; able to choose appropriate tests and perform basic statistical analyses on real data;
5. have an overview of the concepts of screening and diagnostic tests.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. illustrate the fundamental concepts and principles that underpin the central dogma of molecular biology and the basic concepts of gene expression;
2. describe the structure and function of genes, and the mechanisms of gene regulation in prokaryotes and eukaryotes;
3. describe the basic principles and applications of the common molecular techniques and tools;
4. perform experiment tasks independently by following the operating procedures and laboratory safety practices;
5. conduct basic analysis and interpretation of experimental data.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. identify the ethical issues or dilemmas in a given situation;
2. evaluate the decisions and practices of others in cases demonstrating violation of ethics;
3. use the ethical principles as guidance to make justified decisions in resolving ethical questions;
4. consider and respect alternative viewpoints of contentious issues.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. demonstrate good laboratory etiquettes, and develop an awareness on the way to work in the laboratory in a safe and considerate manner;
2. implement lab safety measures, organize their workstation, and complete laboratory records;
3. apply the principles of the basic and commonly used molecular, cellular and microscopy techniques through completion of assigned tasks, conduct experiments with the learnt techniques and operate the relevant equipment independently and with good attitude, competence, and generate data with high accuracy;
4. understand the proper practice in accessing and handling laboratory animals;
5. keep good laboratory records and prepare a general laboratory report.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. describe the fundamental principles of pharmacodynamics, pharmacokinetics and toxicology;
2. explain the molecular, cellular and physiological mechanisms underlying the pharmacological and toxic actions of drugs;
3. apply pharmacodynamics and pharmacokinetics concepts to explain therapeutic applications, adverse effects, contraindications and drug-drug interactions for major classes of drug.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. demonstrate a thorough understanding of the normal physiological functions of the human body systems, and how the normal body function is maintained through the integrative control of the various systems;
2. explain how the derangement of the body functions would lead to the development of diseases (i.e. mechanisms in the pathogenesis of diseases);
3. identify and explain the disease presentations and biochemical changes;
4. describe the parameters of measurements and the methods (or the assays) commonly used for the disease diagnosis and health monitoring.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. demonstrate a thorough understanding of the normal physiological functions of the human body systems, and how the normal body function is maintained through the integrative control of the various systems;
2. explain how the derangement of the body functions would lead to the development of diseases (i.e. mechanisms in the pathogenesis of diseases);
3. identify and explain the disease presentations and biochemical changes;
4. describe the parameters of measurements and the methods (or the assays) commonly used for the disease diagnosis and health monitoring.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. have a basic understanding of the identification, production, and quality control procedures of Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) and herbal products;
2. have a basic understanding of development and commercialization of natural products in promoting health against major diseases;
3. have an appreciation of the philosophy of TCM, in particular medicinal herbs;
4. explain and analyze the pharmacognostic information from different sources, including scientific journals, historical sources, internet and company information.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. illustrate the main components and functions of the immune system;
2. explain the major concepts of immunology and discuss how the immune system works;
3. categorize the major human diseases associated with abnormalities of immune system;
4. discuss the main principles and applications of immunotherapy to different diseases.

After completing this course, students will be able to:
1. compare the characteristics of various microorganisms, including their metabolism and life cycle;
2. assess the factors that contribute to pathogenicity and virulence, as well as their impact on disease transmission;
3. evaluate the different technologies used for handling microorganism specimens;
4. evaluate the common strategies and comprehend the underlying principles for diagnosing, treating, and preventing infectious diseases;
5. apply the fundamental concepts and methods in microbiology to solve problems and address challenges like antibiotic resistance and vaccine development;
6. evaluate the scientific principles that underlie matters of policy or public concern involving microbiology.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. evaluate and sketch experimental designs;
2. decide for and apply appropriate statistical analysis methods on given data;
3. evaluate and appraise published scientific work; recognize and criticize problematic hypothesis;
4. apply the basic skills in different scientific writings, compose manuscripts;
5. adopt proper methods when formulating scientific research, and develop an appropriate attitude essential for a biomedical scientist.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. have a basic understanding of the classification of different types of human cancer;
2. gain knowledge of different hallmarks of human cancer;
3. have an in-depth understanding of the different classes of genes involved in cancer development;
4. appreciate the importance of advanced genetic and bioinformatic tools in cancer research;
5. learn the latest advances in cancer therapy.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. describe the cellular processes and regulatory mechanisms that control development and reproduction, and how they impact human health and disease;
2. design and conduct experiments, collect and analyze data, and develop the practical skills needed for research or clinical settings ;
3. analyze, interpret, and present their experimental results in a clear and compelling way, and develop the skills to discuss the findings;
4. analyze and present the latest research in developmental and reproductive biology, and learn to critically evaluate the evidence and extract key insights;
5. explain the implications of biomedical research findings in the field of developmental and reproductive biology.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. have a basic understanding of the structure and functions of the central and peripheral nervous systems at the neuronal and systems levels;
2. have an appreciation of the complexity of the nervous system and some major current trends in neuroscientific research;
3. have an appreciation of the interdisciplinary nature of neuroscience;
4. have some basic understanding of the aetiology of some common disorders of the nervous system and their current treatment strategies.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. understand the fundamental principles and components of regenerative medicine;
2. understand the origin, characteristics and therapeutic potential of embryonic and adult stem cells;
3. describe the potential of stem cell therapy in neurological, cardiovascular, musculoskeletal and other human disorders;
4. describe the design, fabrication and biomaterials selection criteria for tissue engineering scaffolds;
5. discuss the challenges of in vivo implantation of biomaterials and scale-up issues relating to human clinical applications.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. describe the mechanisms that regulate the cardiovascular biology systems;
2. identify diseases associated with cardiovascular and metabolic biology , and principles of different pharmacological treatments;
3. explain and interpret the cellular mechanisms underlying the available treatment options;
4. apply physiological and pharmacological concepts to design efficacious therapeutics for different cardiovascular diseases with reduced side effects.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. 
describe a general overview of the quality management system, and the basics of Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP) for medicinal products for human use;
2. name the critical quality attributes for quality control for conventional biologics, understand the rationale of quality control strategies, facility requirements, and design of premises, as well as personnel training;
3. differentiate GMP for conventional biologics and for Advanced Therapy Products (ATPs);
4. 
illustrate the challenges in handling and processing biological drugs and ATPs.
​

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. 
describe the basic principles in forensic science, and illustrate the application of scientific disciplines to forensic science;
2. apply forensic sciences to crime scene investigation and reconstruction, including recognition, collection, identification, and preservation of physical evidence;
3. illustrate the roles of forensic scientists and police in court cases and the use of scientific evidence in a legal context.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. appreciate pathologic principles such as apoptosis, necrosis, inflammation, hyperplasia and neoplasia;
2. describe common pathology features of macroscopic specimens and microscopic specimens;
3. apply pathology knowledge to laboratory investigation, disease prevention and patient management.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. understand the principles, protocols and scope of application of the state-of-the-art instruments that are frequently used in biomedical research;
2. understand how to accurately and appropriately use the instruments, for analyzing data generated during the experiments;
3. deep understanding on using instrumental analysis for addressing scientific questions.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. define molecular genetics; recall the characteristics of the various techniques, compare and contrast their functions including advantages and deficiencies in specific applications;
2. describe recent advancement of molecular techniques, and suggest appropriate techniques for therapeutic monitoring or diagnosis;
3. demonstrate the ability to handle experiments independently, provide critiques and new ideas in the written report;
4. critically challenge the issues pertaining to the applications of the various techniques, and their long-term impact on risk assessment and management in public health.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. outline the principles of omics techniques including bioinformatics, genomics and proteomics;
2. analyse and interpret data generated by different omics techniques and algorithms, and discuss the strength and weakness of different omics techniques in biomedical research and clinical practice;
3. realize and discuss the importance of selection of data and strategy of data collection and labeling in bioinformatics and machine learning.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. state the key events in the advances of drug development;
2. describe the drug development process;
3. compare and contrast structure-based and ligand-based drug design;
4. list and apply methods in lead optimisation;
5. describe the methods used in pre-clinical studies and their essence;
6. provide critique of regulation for new drug design, preclinical research and clinical trials.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. learn the genetic basis of monogenic disorders, chromosomal anomalies and complex multifactorial diseases – including their inheritance pattern and clinical manifestations;
2. understand the importance of genetic testing and screening on plans for management and treatment;
3. develop an understanding of pedigree construction and analysis, and the importance of genetic counselling in medicine and family risk assessment.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. recognize and have a deep understanding of the multi-faceted aspects of the biomedical technology industry;
2. identify new opportunities and challenges in the biomedical technology industry for new drug, biologic, and medical device development including new products, research and development;
3. deepen their experiences in this industry by personal sharing from people engaged in this industry.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. describe the essence of managing health services organizations;
2. elaborate key management principles and strategies;
3. discuss specific examples relevant to health services management in Hong Kong.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. integrate both knowledge and skills learnt in previous years of study;
2. conduct an independent research project under supervision;
3. formulate a research hypothesis;
4. design an experiment to test the hypothesis;
5. execute a well-planned experiment and keep it in good progress;
6. demonstrate skills in problem-solving, collection and accurate record of data, critical analysis and interpretation of results, and retrieval of useful information;
7. use library and other tools to search for existing body of research relevant to their topics;
8. demonstrate good team spirit and communication skills in scientific research.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. integrate both knowledge and skills learnt in previous years of study;
2. conduct an independent research project under supervision;
3. demonstrate improved skills in problem-solving, collection and accurate record of data, critical analysis and interpretation of results, and retrieval of useful information;
4. use library and other tools to search for existing body of research relevant to their topics;
5. demonstrate good team spirit and improved communication skills in scientific research;
6. present a seminar on the results of the research project;
7. prepare a thesis (draft, edit, format, check for errors) and make contribution in further biomedical research.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. gain working experience in a workplace setting;
2. demonstrate professional ethics and judgment, as well as competencies through applying technical and soft skills to solve authentic problems;
3. appreciate the broad spectrum of work that the transferrable skills and knowledge acquired from the programme be applied to jobs related to strategic management and entrepreneurship, and health services and consultation;
4. reflect on their workplace experience for professional development and life-long learning.

